@node Intro "Introduction"

 This  small  utility  generates a clean copy of IBrowse's cache 2.x in a new
 location  defined  by  the  user:  the above mentioned copy will contain the
 files "DataBases/GlobalCache" and all those of the cache that should remain.
 You  can't  run this program if there are other copy working or "IBrowse" is
 running.

 This  tool  supports  so much the v20.3 of the file "GlobalCache (including,
 the "Cookies" file in the clean copy) as v20.5 introduced with IBrowse 2.4.

@endnode

@node Req "Requirements"

 The  program  requires  a system with  Kickstart 2.1 (v38) as minimum and it
 uses the "Exec" & "DOS" libraries, as well as, optionally:

  *Ā"Asl",  to  open the filerequest for to set the enviroment vars IBcc_FROM
     and  IBcc_TO,  if  theses  don't  exists  (remember:   choose  ONLY  the
     directory, NOT a file inside this one).

  *Ā"Icon",  to  read  the  icon tooltypes if the program is started from the
    Workbench.

  *Ā"Locale", for the local support.

--

 (*1)ĀDo not try to re-baptize the program... his name is "IBcc" ;-).

@endnode

@node Ins "Installation"

 My  personal recomendation is that you copy the executable "IBcc" in "C:" if
 you  think  to use  it  habitually  from the CLI/Shell, "IBcc_xxxx.guide" in
 "Locale:Help/xxxx" drawer renaming the file as "IBcc.guide" and the catalogs
 in  "Locale:Catalogs/xxxx",  where  "xxxx"  represents to  the corresponding
 language i.e. "franńais" ;).

 If  you  want  to  avoid  to  introduce  in  every session the source (where
 IBrowse's  cache is located) and the destination (where you want to generate
 the  clean copy) directory, you can use "C:SetEnv" command, an editor...  or
 "IBcc"╣,  for to set the enviroment vars IBcc_FROM and IBcc_TO respectively,
 copying later the above mentioned files in "ENVARC:".

 @{u}Curiosities@{uu}:

 *ĀIBcc's  previous  versions:   if  you  has  used someone of these versions
   delete  (this is safe) the file "IBcc.prefs" of "ENV:" and "ENVARC:" since
   already  it  isn't in use and update the installed catalogs  (includes new
   strings and discard some obsolete).

--

 (*1)ĀIf  the  env  variables  don't  exist,  the  program  will be generated
      automatically,  and  for  this  order,  from  the  arguments  (CLI)  or
      tooltypes  values  (Workbench), of introduced via Asl filerequests that
      it  will try to open the own program or assigning, finally, the default
      values  ("SYS:Internet/IBrowse/Cache/"  and  "T:"  respectively, that I
      believe reasonable enough).

@endnode

@node Uso "Use"

 The  program  is  essentially  thought  to  be  executed  from the CLI/Shell
 environment (preceded or not with the command "C:RUN") or to be invoked from
 a script.  However, you can run it from the Workbench also.

 The template is:

                    @{fg highlight}FROM/K,TO/K,VERBOSE/S,QUIET/S@{fg text}

 FROM, keyword

   IBrowse's cache path.
   I.e., "SYS:Internet/IBrowse/Cache/".

 TO, keyword

   IBrowse's clean cache path.
   I.e., "T:".

 VERBOSE, switch

   It  offers more detailed information about the task (blocks "I"╣ detected,
   his  position  inside  the  "GlobalCache"  file  so  much  in  decimal  as
   hexadecimal format, the original filename copied and his size).

   If  you  don't  use  it, the program will limit itself to show the name of
   program  and version, the files copied (name and path) and a final summary
   with  the  number  of parsed blocks, time that has been late and number of
   recovered files.

 QUIET, switch

   It  suppresses  all  the  messages, include yours those of errors/warnings
   that are replaced with AmigaDOS exit codes for to use from a script.  This
   switch  is  incompatible with the switch VERBOSE, preferring the latter if
   both are in use.

 I. e.

                IBcc FROM DH2:IBrowse/Cache/ TO RAM: VERBOSE
                IBcc > RAM:Output.txt FROM MyDisk:IBCache/

 From   the  Workbench,  all  the  arguments  mentioned  previously  for  the
 CLI/Shell, they work as tooltypes with two important peculiarities:

 *ĀIt  is  MANDATORY to define correctly a tooltype named WINDOW:  it defines
   the  info  destination  shown  to  the user.  If this isn't defined Hisoft
   Basic  will  generate  the  error "Runtime Error 52 on #257".  The default
   value  is "WINDOW=CON:0/50/640/150/IBcc" but you can modify it, already be
   to  change  the size of the window, already it be to choose another device
   (as "WINDOW=RAM:Output.txt" for example).

 *ĀQUIET does not return the AmigaDOS exit codes commented, so that on having
   used  this  option  simply  you  will  see  an  empty window.  Try instead
   "WINDOW=NIL:" ;)

 @{u}Curiosities@{uu}

 *ĀIf  on  having  tried to start the program it hears a beep and the program
   ends,  the problem will be due to a serious error:  the program can't open
   the "DOS" library.

 *ĀIf  you  start  the  program from the Workbench, the window will be closed
   automatically to four seconds of stopping/ending doing his work.

--
   (*1)ĀThe "GlobalCache" file seems to be formed by a header and essentially
        four types of blocks ...  since it is a private format, and it is not
        the scope of this document either, only I will say that the block "I"
        is  the  only  one  that seems to contain information about the files
        saved  in the cache directory and the only one of which "IBcc" parses
        his contents.

@endnode

@node  Notas "Notes"

 *ĀThe original version was developped by Marnix under AMOS.

 *ĀThis version has been developped
   with Hisoft Basic 2.1/AmigaOS 3.9/CodeWatcher 1.4 under WinUAE.

 * David Rey/Tßctica did several suggestions about
   the english strings (interface) and IBcc's features.

 *ĀThis version offers:

   - A nice icon.

   -ĀConfiguration via environment vars,
     tooltypes (Workbench) and arguments (CLI/Shell).

   - Locale support
     AmigaGuide docs ("english" and spanish),
     english, french and spanish interface.

   - New routine to explore the "GlobalCache" file
     (simpler, trustworthy and more fast).

   -ĀYou can interrupt their task in any moment sending 
     a Ctrl-C signal, without loss of resources, or I wait for it ;).

   - Interaction with scripts that invoke it
     (returning exit codes for to evaluate).

   -ĀThe program reduces his priority in one unit
     to avoid to overload the microprocessor.

   - The program verifies:

     . initially the source and destination
       directories exists and are not the same.
     . that the"GlobalCache" file exists,
       their basic format is valid/acquaintance and that isn't empty.

 * Future plans?

   None.

 *ĀPackage  (and  specially,  the  english  AmigaGuide documentation done via
   Reverso  5) without warranties:  the user assumes entirely the risk of the
   use.   If  he  entrusts  sufficiently  in  this tool you can write a small
   script  that invokes it and once finished the work deletes IBrowse's cache
   and copies/moves to his place this clean copy.

 * My website
   http://www.mundo-r.com/amispatra/

@endnode

